  "summary": "Dr. Nicholson ties Frankie to a damaged oak chair and reveals his plan to murder both her and Bobby. He intends to stage a car accident on a disused road leading to a quarry, making it appear that Frankie and her driver crashed off a cliff. Nicholson notes that Bobby’s high morphine tolerance is a setback, but he plans to ensure their bodies are found cold. Frankie attempts to bluff Nicholson by claiming she told Roger Baskington-French about his actions, but Nicholson dismisses the threat. He also reveals that his wife, Moira, is still alive, though her future is uncertain. Nicholson then locks the attic door and leaves to finalize his plan.\n\nWhile alone, Bobby and Frankie discuss whether Sylvia was involved in Henry Baskington-French's death. Bobby then realizes that the man who visited them was not Nicholson, but an imposter. Based on the appearance of the man's ears, Bobby concludes the imposter is Roger Baskington-French. Suddenly, a body falls through the skylight; it is Baxter. To hide Baxter's presence, Bobby instructs him to throw one of Bobby's boots toward the broken glass under the skylight and hide under the bed. When the imposter enters, he sees the boot and the broken glass but assumes Bobby performed a \"juggling act\" to throw it. The imposter checks the ropes and leaves. Once the door is closed, Baxter emerges from under the bed and uses a folding knife to untie Frankie and Bobby.",
